  "prompt": "How much equity (%) should be in the employee pool at an early stage (angel round) company?",
  "response": "For an early-stage (angel round) startup, the typical employee equity pool is usually between 10-15% of the total company equity. Here's a more detailed breakdown:\n\n1. Standard Range:\n- 10-15% for early-stage startups\n- Allows for future hiring and employee retention\n\n2. Factors Influencing Pool Size:\n- Company stage\n- Industry\n- Expected future funding rounds\n- Hiring plans\n\n3. Typical Equity Allocation:\n- Founders: 50-70%\n- Employee Pool: 10-15%\n- Investors: 15-40%\n\n4. Considerations:\n- Pool should be large enough to attract talent\n- Flexible enough to accommodate future hires\n- Can be expanded in subsequent rounds\n\n5. Individual Employee Grants:\n- Early employees: 1-2%\n- Key executives: 0.5-1.5%\n- Later employees: 0.1-0.5%\n\n6. Best Practices:\n- Create a transparent equity strategy\n- Have a clear vesting schedule\n- Regularly review and adjust pool\n\nRemember, these are general guidelines and can vary based on specific circumstances.",
